      "question": "For a grouped frequency distribution, the empirical relationship between the three measures of central tendency is given by $3 \\times \\text{Median} = \\text{Mode} + 2 \\times \\text{Mean}$. If for a specific distribution, the mean is $25.5$ and the median is $26$, then the mode of the distribution is:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the given values: $\\text{Mean} = 25.5$ and $\\text{Median} = 26$.",
          "Use the empirical formula: $3 \\times \\text{Median} = \\text{Mode} + 2 \\times \\text{Mean}$.",
          "Substitute the known values into the formula: $3(26) = \\text{Mode} + 2(25.5)$.",
          "Calculate the products: $78 = \\text{Mode} + 51$.",
          "Solve for the mode: $\\text{Mode} = 78 - 51 = 27$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$3 \\times \\text{Median} = \\text{Mode} + 2 \\times \\text{Mean} \\\\ 3(26) = \\text{Mode} + 2(25.5) \\\\ 78 = \\text{Mode} + 51 \\\\ \\text{Mode} = 78 - 51 \\\\ \\text{Mode} = 27$"
      },
      "topic": "Statistics",
      "subtopic": "Empirical relationship between Mean, Median and Mode",
      "marks": 1,
